He goes by Logos.

247
00:15:57,632 --> 00:16:01,000
WOMAN: You're sure
no-one followed you?

248
00:16:01,002 --> 00:16:02,868
LOGOS: I'm sure.

249
00:16:02,870 --> 00:16:05,571
- (BEEPING)
- (KNOCKS AT DOOR)

250
00:16:08,776 --> 00:16:10,610
(BEEPING CONTINUES)

251
00:16:18,553 --> 00:16:21,120
MAN: The simplest explanation

252
00:16:21,122 --> 00:16:23,589
is that we're trying
to spread the truth.

253
00:16:23,591 --> 00:16:25,324
There's an entire world
of citizens

254
00:16:25,326 --> 00:16:27,326
just outside these doors
that believe

255
00:16:27,328 --> 00:16:30,997
they live a perfect life
in a perfect world.

256
00:16:30,999 --> 00:16:33,232
But you're not like them.

257
00:16:33,234 --> 00:16:35,034
And neither are we.

258
00:16:36,070 --> 00:16:38,371
It's clear you're not on
your Maintenance,

259
00:16:38,373 --> 00:16:41,841
that you're opening your eyes
for the first time.

260
00:16:41,843 --> 00:16:44,277
But I'm on my Maintenance.

261
00:16:44,279 --> 00:16:45,711
I've never missed a dose.

262
00:16:45,713 --> 00:16:48,881
- That's impossible.
- It's true.

263
00:16:50,585 --> 00:16:53,853
I don't know how or why
this is happening to me.

264
00:16:55,056 --> 00:16:56,789
We are just like you.

265
00:16:56,791 --> 00:16:58,991
This is where you belong.

266
00:16:58,993 --> 00:17:00,960
You can go back to your life...

267
00:17:01,929 --> 00:17:03,829
..your book,

268
00:17:03,831 --> 00:17:06,299
or you can join us.

269
00:17:07,769 --> 00:17:10,603
Everyone in this world
deserves the chance

270
00:17:10,605 --> 00:17:13,606
to see things the way we do.

271
00:17:13,608 --> 00:17:15,041
You know that.

272
00:17:15,043 --> 00:17:18,411
- How?
- Follow us.

273
00:17:23,151 --> 00:17:25,418
(COMPUTER TRILLS)

274
00:17:25,420 --> 00:17:28,854
Are you developing an antidote
to the Maintenance?

275
00:17:28,856 --> 00:17:32,258
We've created a method to reduce
the efficacy of the Maintenance.

276
00:17:32,260 --> 00:17:34,960
So, yes, an antidote of sorts.

277
00:17:34,962 --> 00:17:37,296
Medorin's been instrumental
in the process.

278
00:17:37,298 --> 00:17:38,731
She's a polymath.

279
00:17:38,733 --> 00:17:41,267
She knows more about the Code
and Maintenance than anyone.

280
00:17:41,269 --> 00:17:42,968
Thanks to the manual we located

281
00:17:42,970 --> 00:17:46,138
of a man who worked very closely
with the Pilot many years ago.

282
00:17:46,140 --> 00:17:48,040
Before humans lived forever.

283
00:17:48,042 --> 00:17:51,210
His shorthand was a bit
difficult to interpret,

284
00:17:51,212 --> 00:17:53,679
but ultimately,
after some trial and error,

285
00:17:53,681 --> 00:17:55,614
we were able to get it right.

286
00:17:55,616 --> 00:17:58,918
- Who is this person?
- Helias was his name.

287
00:18:00,188 --> 00:18:02,455
Arcade is
our resident historian.

288
00:18:02,457 --> 00:18:04,423
There's not much about
the creation of Alisandre

289
00:18:04,425 --> 00:18:06,225
that he doesn't know.

290
00:18:06,227 --> 00:18:09,829
Sometimes I think there are
far more unknowns than knowns.

291
00:18:09,831 --> 00:18:12,565
Originally, Helias worked
closely with the Pilot

292
00:18:12,567 --> 00:18:14,900
in the development of the Code
and Maintenance.

293
00:18:14,902 --> 00:18:18,404
But once the Code was completed
and implemented worldwide,

294
00:18:18,406 --> 00:18:21,140
Helias discovered that the Pilot
had gone further.

295
00:18:21,142 --> 00:18:22,808
The Pilot had modified genes

296
00:18:22,810 --> 00:18:25,678
that had nothing to do with
health or longevity.

297
00:18:25,680 --> 00:18:28,047
Helias started asking questions.

298
00:18:28,049 --> 00:18:30,583
The Pilot of course
didn't approve of his probe.

299
00:18:30,585 --> 00:18:34,086
The trust was gone.
They parted ways.

300
00:18:34,088 --> 00:18:35,921
The Pilot began
to wipe the minds

301
00:18:35,923 --> 00:18:38,457
of all the original mortals.

302
00:18:38,459 --> 00:18:41,394
Helias became the only immortal,
other than the Pilot,

303
00:18:41,396 --> 00:18:43,529
to have memories
of mortal existence.

304
00:18:43,531 --> 00:18:45,398
The Pilot collected
and stored the information

305
00:18:45,400 --> 00:18:46,966
in his data centre.

306
00:18:46,968 --> 00:18:49,201
Where is he now?

307
00:18:49,203 --> 00:18:51,437
The Pilot eventually had Helias
captured and rehabilitated.

308
00:18:51,439 --> 00:18:54,006
That's a nice way to say
they erased his mind.

309
00:18:54,008 --> 00:18:57,877
- Killed him without killing him.
- MASIM: We all see it.

310
00:18:57,879 --> 00:18:59,078
What he showed us -

311
00:18:59,080 --> 00:19:03,215
when you reduce Maintenance,
you begin to change.

312
00:19:03,217 --> 00:19:05,651
Maintenance contains
mood stabilisers.

313
00:19:05,653 --> 00:19:07,820
So you essentially become

314
00:19:07,822 --> 00:19:10,523
a muted version of the person
you're supposed to be.

315
00:19:10,525 --> 00:19:13,225
Which is why we want to alter
the Maintenance,

316
00:19:13,227 --> 00:19:14,460
lower its potency,

317
00:19:14,462 --> 00:19:16,829
so that everyone in Alisandre
can experience

318
00:19:16,831 --> 00:19:18,063
for a few moments

319
00:19:18,065 --> 00:19:21,734
a version of what real
human existence feels like.

320
00:19:21,736 --> 00:19:23,436
And then what?

321
00:19:23,438 --> 00:19:26,205
Well, removing the Maintenance
only gives us

322
00:19:26,207 --> 00:19:28,874
an edited version
of the human experience.

323
00:19:28,876 --> 00:19:32,445
None of us can really understand
what it feels like to be human

324
00:19:32,447 --> 00:19:36,182
without the stakes
of human life.

325
00:19:36,184 --> 00:19:38,150
Without being mortal.

326
00:19:39,821 --> 00:19:43,823
Are you talking about destroying
the Code itself?

327
00:19:47,228 --> 00:19:48,994
WOMAN: I remember you telling me

328
00:19:48,996 --> 00:19:52,698
that Helias's belief
in mortal religion was flawed.

329
00:19:53,534 --> 00:19:55,701
I didn't know you could still
remember that long ago.

330
00:19:55,703 --> 00:19:57,470
I thought we'd removed
that data.

331
00:19:57,472 --> 00:20:00,206
I remember you telling me
that mortals needed religion

332
00:20:00,208 --> 00:20:02,641
because they were afraid
of dying.

333
00:20:03,811 --> 00:20:07,213
But with immortal beings,
there is no fear of death

334
00:20:07,215 --> 00:20:09,682
and so no need for religion.

335
00:20:10,518 --> 00:20:12,451
Religious citizens talked about

336
00:20:12,453 --> 00:20:15,821
being alive
for a God-given purpose,

337
00:20:15,823 --> 00:20:19,325
that their time on Earth
was intentionally difficult,

338
00:20:19,327 --> 00:20:24,697
and that they were each given
a soul which was immortal.

339
00:20:25,766 --> 00:20:29,568
That was the logic
of primitive minds.

340
00:20:29,570 --> 00:20:32,538
Of course I always knew
that science and technology

341
00:20:32,540 --> 00:20:34,073
were the real gods.

342
00:20:34,075 --> 00:20:36,509
Their god never worked for
the greater good of the world.

343
00:20:36,511 --> 00:20:38,177
Mine always did.

344
00:20:38,179 --> 00:20:40,579
Humans... Um...

345
00:20:40,581 --> 00:20:44,950
The... the human condition
needed to evolve.

346
00:20:46,320 --> 00:20:49,655
What about Helias?
What did he believe?

347
00:20:50,391 --> 00:20:52,958
You're full of questions
tonight.

348
00:20:54,295 --> 00:20:56,762
Why don't we get back
to the game?

349
00:21:09,410 --> 00:21:11,677
At the beginning,

350
00:21:11,679 --> 00:21:14,547
Helias was as secular
as they come.

351
00:21:14,549 --> 00:21:18,150
When we were at Harvard,
he never mentioned religion.

352
00:21:18,152 --> 00:21:19,251
Ever.

353
00:21:19,253 --> 00:21:22,688
Well, he was a true scholar

354
00:21:22,690 --> 00:21:25,991
and he believed that technology
would be the answer

355
00:21:25,993 --> 00:21:27,726
to human suffering.

356
00:21:27,728 --> 00:21:31,931
Many people started to move
toward that direction

357
00:21:31,933 --> 00:21:33,899
at that time.

358
00:21:34,902 --> 00:21:37,503
Helias started to believe
that the...

359
00:21:37,505 --> 00:21:41,273
..the human body is a machine.

360
00:21:41,275 --> 00:21:44,376
And he was right -
we started to work on this idea

361
00:21:44,378 --> 00:21:48,013
that this machine
could be perfected

362
00:21:48,015 --> 00:21:52,418
so that it could go on and on
forever.

363
00:21:52,420 --> 00:21:55,220
Now, that was
an exciting time.

364
00:21:55,990 --> 00:21:57,823
When we first started
our company

365
00:21:57,825 --> 00:21:59,792
and we...

366
00:21:59,794 --> 00:22:05,297
..we grew our group of
scientists and geneticists,

367
00:22:05,299 --> 00:22:06,732
we started to feel that

368
00:22:06,734 --> 00:22:09,868
we were really going
to be able to do it.

369
00:22:09,870 --> 00:22:13,305
For the greater good, right?

370
00:22:15,409 --> 00:22:17,676
Of course.

371
00:22:18,412 --> 00:22:20,379
(WIND WHISTLES)

372
00:22:20,381 --> 00:22:23,782
(MYSTERIOUS MUSIC)

373
00:22:40,968 --> 00:22:43,535
Wake up. Can you hear me?
Can you hear me?

374
00:22:43,537 --> 00:22:45,838
Can you hear me?
Wake up. Wake up.

375
00:22:45,840 --> 00:22:49,408
Wake up. Wake up.
Can you hear me? Wake up.

376
00:22:58,486 --> 00:23:00,285
(GASPS)

377
00:23:11,332 --> 00:23:14,733
(WISTFUL MUSIC)

378
00:23:33,788 --> 00:23:36,055
Where's your book?

379
00:23:37,191 --> 00:23:39,191
I'm sorry?

380
00:23:39,193 --> 00:23:41,593
Your book. What was it?

381
00:23:41,595 --> 00:23:43,462
(CHUCKLES)

382
00:23:43,464 --> 00:23:45,330
'Being and Nothingness'.

383
00:23:46,300 --> 00:23:48,000
That was it.

384
00:23:48,869 --> 00:23:51,370
Too much on my mind to read.

385
00:23:52,640 --> 00:23:54,373
I know the feeling.

386
00:23:55,576 --> 00:23:57,776
You do?

387
00:23:59,213 --> 00:24:00,879
I do.

388
00:24:02,116 --> 00:24:03,949
Who are you?

389
00:24:04,685 --> 00:24:06,985
My name is Akae.

390
00:24:06,987 --> 00:24:08,854
Logos.

391
00:24:09,957 --> 00:24:12,791
- Nice to meet you, Logos.
- Likewise.

392
00:24:15,329 --> 00:24:17,196
Can I ask you something?

393
00:24:17,198 --> 00:24:19,231
You already have.

394
00:24:21,502 --> 00:24:23,702
That's true.

395
00:24:23,704 --> 00:24:26,405
But something a bit more...

396
00:24:26,407 --> 00:24:28,574
..personal.

397
00:24:28,576 --> 00:24:31,110
Depends on what you want to ask.

398
00:24:40,321 --> 00:24:42,287
Do you take your Maintenance?

399
00:24:44,325 --> 00:24:45,758
Why would you ask that?

400
00:24:45,760 --> 00:24:47,926
It just seems like you don't.

401
00:24:48,662 --> 00:24:50,362
Do you?

402
00:24:53,934 --> 00:24:57,102
Seems like a question
neither of us wants to answer.

403
00:24:58,372 --> 00:25:02,374
But I get the sense
we've got a lot in common.

404
00:25:04,979 --> 00:25:08,213
(COMPUTER BEEPS SOFTLY)

405
00:25:08,215 --> 00:25:11,850
I need to understand
how you plan on doing this.

406
00:25:11,852 --> 00:25:14,019
You've figured out a way
to reduce the Maintenance,

407
00:25:14,021 --> 00:25:18,524
but getting access to the supply
is impossible.

408
00:25:18,526 --> 00:25:21,026
Difficult, yeah.

409
00:25:21,028 --> 00:25:24,263
But I wouldn't say impossible.

410
00:25:25,399 --> 00:25:26,832
Few things truly are,

411
00:25:26,834 --> 00:25:29,201
so long as you have faith.

412
00:25:33,707 --> 00:25:35,908
I scouted the facility
and used the fader

413
00:25:35,910 --> 00:25:38,210
to scan for vulnerabilities
in the structure.

414
00:25:38,212 --> 00:25:40,379
As a terraforming engineer,
I'm sure you're well aware...

415
00:25:40,381 --> 00:25:41,980
That there are no weaknesses.

416
00:25:41,982 --> 00:25:43,749
The construction materials
of the building

417
00:25:43,751 --> 00:25:45,350
were embedded with
synthetic composites

418
00:25:45,352 --> 00:25:47,519
that make getting in
from the outside impossible.

419
00:25:47,521 --> 00:25:51,523
So, I used the fader to scan
the surrounding infrastructures.

420
00:25:51,525 --> 00:25:52,925
LOGOS: What did you find?

421
00:25:52,927 --> 00:25:54,526
All of the capital buildings
are connected

422
00:25:54,528 --> 00:25:56,161
by a sort of underground maze.

423
00:25:56,163 --> 00:25:59,064
Wouldn't it be just as difficult
to gain access to those tunnels?

424
00:25:59,066 --> 00:26:00,833
Yeah, unless you knew someone

425
00:26:00,835 --> 00:26:03,468
who worked in
one of the capital buildings.

426
00:26:03,470 --> 00:26:05,537
In fact, as all of you know,

427
00:26:05,539 --> 00:26:09,341
Alisandre is currently
celebrating its 200th year

428
00:26:09,343 --> 00:26:11,543
living with
the gift of immortality

429
00:26:11,545 --> 00:26:13,545
that was given to us
by the Pilot.

430
00:26:13,547 --> 00:26:17,115
Speaking of which, follow me and
we'll head to Shem application

431
00:26:17,117 --> 00:26:19,551
so we can get a firsthand look.

432
00:26:24,291 --> 00:26:28,093
Uh, I'll be back
in just one moment.

433
00:26:28,095 --> 00:26:32,164
Yum, Chasan will take you ahead.
I'll be back.

434
00:26:37,104 --> 00:26:39,171
Follow me.

435
00:26:41,008 --> 00:26:42,641
What are you doing here?

436
00:26:42,643 --> 00:26:44,142
The answer is yes.

437
00:26:44,144 --> 00:26:46,511
What are you talking about?

438
00:26:46,513 --> 00:26:49,481
You asked me on the train
if I took my Maintenance.

439
00:26:49,483 --> 00:26:51,450
I do.

440
00:26:51,452 --> 00:26:53,385
Do you?

441
00:26:55,489 --> 00:26:57,322
We saw Chasan leading the tour.

442
00:26:57,324 --> 00:26:59,458
Is everything OK?

443
00:26:59,460 --> 00:27:00,893
Everything's fine.

444
00:27:00,895 --> 00:27:02,394
We were just wrapping up.

445
00:27:02,396 --> 00:27:05,364
I can't do this today.
Let's talk tomorrow.

446
00:27:05,366 --> 00:27:07,266
I'll be here.

447
00:27:13,774 --> 00:27:16,074
How does it feel?

448
00:27:17,311 --> 00:27:18,744
How does what feel?

449
00:27:18,746 --> 00:27:20,679
Being identical twins.

450
00:27:20,681 --> 00:27:22,047
It's a very rare thing.

451
00:27:22,049 --> 00:27:24,316
We've always felt extra special
because of that.

452
00:27:24,318 --> 00:27:28,220
It's a bond that few understand
and that we both cherish.

453
00:27:28,222 --> 00:27:30,789
Are you scared of losing that
someday?

454
00:27:30,791 --> 00:27:32,824
Losing what?

455
00:27:32,826 --> 00:27:34,526
The bond you share.

456
00:27:35,963 --> 00:27:39,498
That's impossible.
We'll always be the same.

457
00:27:39,500 --> 00:27:41,816
Unless the Pilot decides that

458
00:27:41,818 --> 00:27:44,135
one of you is ready for your
confirmation before the other.

459
00:27:44,138 --> 00:27:46,738
He would never do that.

460
00:27:46,740 --> 00:27:49,374
Of course.

461
00:27:59,887 --> 00:28:03,922
What happened yesterday?
Why was he there?

462
00:28:03,924 --> 00:28:05,457
AKAE ON SPEAKER:
<i>He wanted to tell me</i>

463
00:28:05,459 --> 00:28:09,428
<i>he was on his Maintenance,
and asked if I was.</i>

464
00:28:09,430 --> 00:28:11,163
And what did you say?

465
00:28:11,899 --> 00:28:14,466
Nothing. We were interrupted.

466
00:28:14,468 --> 00:28:16,101
<i>Anything else?</i>

467
00:28:16,103 --> 00:28:17,836
We agreed to speak later.

468
00:28:17,838 --> 00:28:19,771
Good.

469
00:28:20,808 --> 00:28:23,709
Hopefully you'll be able to
obtain more information then.

470
00:28:26,613 --> 00:28:28,347
Armaros...

471
00:28:29,183 --> 00:28:31,016
<i>..do you ever wonder
what it's like?</i>

472
00:28:31,018 --> 00:28:33,685
(MYSTERIOUS MUSIC)

473
00:28:33,687 --> 00:28:35,153
What are you talking about?

474
00:28:35,155 --> 00:28:37,689
To not be on your Maintenance.

475
00:28:37,691 --> 00:28:39,224
It's just...

476
00:28:39,226 --> 00:28:43,895
The idea of opening up your mind
to its most uncontrolled state,

477
00:28:43,897 --> 00:28:46,431
I wonder how it feels.

478
00:28:47,468 --> 00:28:49,534
I don't ever wonder that.

479
00:28:49,536 --> 00:28:51,203
<i>And you shouldn't either.</i>

480
00:28:51,205 --> 00:28:53,972
<i>Akae, people who do not take
their Maintenance</i>

481
00:28:53,974 --> 00:28:57,642
<i>are broken, defective.</i>

482
00:28:57,644 --> 00:28:59,344
<i>They're disrespecting a gift</i>

483
00:28:59,346 --> 00:29:00,879
<i>that the Pilot
has given to them.</i>

484
00:29:00,881 --> 00:29:06,651
Deciding themselves that somehow
they know more than he does.

485
00:29:07,921 --> 00:29:10,555
<i>They don't.</i>

486
00:29:10,557 --> 00:29:13,525
You're right. They don't.

487
00:29:14,294 --> 00:29:16,795
It was just a crazy thought
I had.

488
00:29:19,733 --> 00:29:22,401
I'm proud of you, Akae.

489
00:29:22,403 --> 00:29:26,605
You are serving Alisandre
and the Pilot well.

490
00:29:28,475 --> 00:29:30,042
Keep up the good work.

491
00:29:30,044 --> 00:29:31,676
(COMMUNICATION DEVICE BEEPS)

492
00:29:31,678 --> 00:29:33,745
(SIGHS)

493
00:29:53,333 --> 00:29:55,434
I wasn't sure you'd be here.

494
00:29:55,436 --> 00:29:57,102
I wasn't either.

495
00:29:58,205 --> 00:30:02,074
So, why are you really here?

496
00:30:05,446 --> 00:30:08,080
There aren't many people
like us.

497
00:30:08,982 --> 00:30:10,515
What do you mean, like us?

498
00:30:10,517 --> 00:30:13,718
People that think
there's something more.

499
00:30:14,521 --> 00:30:17,222
That question
the world around them.

500
00:30:17,224 --> 00:30:20,525
The real reason I'm here is

501
00:30:20,527 --> 00:30:23,195
I have some friends
I think you should meet.

502
00:30:23,964 --> 00:30:25,397
Friends?

503
00:30:25,399 --> 00:30:27,866
People that think the way we do.

504
00:30:29,503 --> 00:30:31,369
But why?

505
00:30:34,208 --> 00:30:37,442
I think you'd be interested
in what they have to say.

506
00:30:38,312 --> 00:30:40,378
They can explain more.

507
00:30:42,616 --> 00:30:44,583
Why should I trust you?

508
00:30:45,519 --> 00:30:47,552
You shouldn't.

509
00:30:47,554 --> 00:30:49,588
You don't have to.

510
00:30:49,590 --> 00:30:53,358
You could walk away right now
and never see me again.

511
00:30:57,264 --> 00:30:59,464
Or you could come with me.

512
00:31:00,801 --> 00:31:04,202
(PULSING MUSIC)

513
00:31:12,079 --> 00:31:13,612
Welcome.

514
00:31:13,614 --> 00:31:14,746
Gergot.

515
00:31:14,748 --> 00:31:16,181
- Logos.
- Akae.

516
00:31:16,183 --> 00:31:18,583
I've been looking forward
to meeting you both.

517
00:31:18,585 --> 00:31:21,453
I wasn't here when you first met
the rest of the group.

518
00:31:21,455 --> 00:31:23,421
I was in the forested area.

519
00:31:23,423 --> 00:31:25,624
- Doing what?
- Foraging.

520
00:31:25,626 --> 00:31:27,058
Foraging?

521
00:31:27,060 --> 00:31:28,393
The Pilot's dietary inventions

522
00:31:28,395 --> 00:31:30,495
are complex in nutrients
and efficient to consume

523
00:31:30,497 --> 00:31:33,398
but they taste
absolutely horrible.

524
00:31:33,400 --> 00:31:35,534
So I've self-trained as a chef.

525
00:31:35,536 --> 00:31:37,435
Obviously it's hard to get
my hands on ingredients

526
00:31:37,437 --> 00:31:40,739
that actually make food
taste good, so I improvise.

527
00:31:40,741 --> 00:31:42,541
Here we are.

528
00:31:45,779 --> 00:31:48,346
- You must be Akae.
- I am.

529
00:31:48,348 --> 00:31:50,682
We're very glad you're here.

530
00:31:51,718 --> 00:31:55,420
Helias believed that we have
an intended purpose on Earth.

531
00:31:55,422 --> 00:31:59,090
He believed to the core of his
being that we're meant to die.

532
00:31:59,092 --> 00:32:02,327
I feel like
I'm walking through my life

533
00:32:02,329 --> 00:32:04,863
as two totally different people.

534
00:32:05,632 --> 00:32:10,168
That there's a part of me
somewhere inside

535
00:32:10,170 --> 00:32:12,270
that I can't quite access.

536
00:32:12,272 --> 00:32:14,439
That's exactly what
Helias thought.

537
00:32:14,441 --> 00:32:18,076
He believed there was a creator
of this universe and of man.

538
00:32:18,078 --> 00:32:21,213
He said that mortals believed
that they each had an essence -

539
00:32:21,215 --> 00:32:22,647
he called it the soul -

540
00:32:22,649 --> 00:32:26,117
which had a purpose given to it
by this creator.

541
00:32:26,119 --> 00:32:27,652
Instead, the Pilot decided

542
00:32:27,654 --> 00:32:30,655
to determine a purpose
for each one of us,

543
00:32:30,657 --> 00:32:33,358
essentially denying us
the right to our own destiny.

544
00:32:33,360 --> 00:32:37,095
And while we still feel
emotions, they're limited.

545
00:32:37,097 --> 00:32:40,131
Mortals experienced more.

546
00:32:40,133 --> 00:32:41,766
Much more.

547
00:32:41,768 --> 00:32:43,768
What's the point?

548
00:32:44,905 --> 00:32:46,338
What do you mean?

549
00:32:46,340 --> 00:32:48,206
While what this man,
Helias, believed

550
00:32:48,208 --> 00:32:50,242
is certainly interesting,

551
00:32:50,244 --> 00:32:52,010
what's the point
in believing in a mortal life

552
00:32:52,012 --> 00:32:55,146
when it's not something
we're genetically capable of?

553
00:32:55,148 --> 00:32:57,449
It just seems futile to me.

554
00:32:59,119 --> 00:33:01,052
I hope she didn't offend you.

555
00:33:01,054 --> 00:33:04,589
No. No. She hasn't.

556
00:33:04,591 --> 00:33:06,658
I like people
that ask big questions,

557
00:33:06,660 --> 00:33:10,629
because big questions
are what we here are all about.

558
00:33:11,465 --> 00:33:15,333
I especially like questions
that I know the answer to.

559
00:33:17,070 --> 00:33:19,037
(WHIRRING AND BEEPING)

560
00:33:23,543 --> 00:33:25,510
MEDORIN: Helias called it
the Code Diffuser.

561
00:33:25,512 --> 00:33:29,447
It was intended to wipe the Code
from the genome.

562
00:33:29,449 --> 00:33:32,150
He created it as a way
to restore mortality.

563
00:33:32,152 --> 00:33:34,352
Why would he do that?

564
00:33:35,088 --> 00:33:39,291
He felt it was a very important
part of the human experience.

565
00:33:39,293 --> 00:33:41,126
Something we are all
missing out on.

566
00:33:41,128 --> 00:33:43,862
Has anyone ever used it before?

567
00:33:43,864 --> 00:33:45,463
He never finished work on it.

568
00:33:45,465 --> 00:33:48,266
This is just a prototype.

569
00:33:48,268 --> 00:33:51,903
We are planning on
restoring Helias's mind data.

570
00:33:51,905 --> 00:33:54,139
But in order to do that,
we need to find Helias.

571
00:33:54,141 --> 00:33:57,475
And when we do, we'll finally
meet the man behind all of this,

572
00:33:57,477 --> 00:33:59,311
finish what he started.

573
00:33:59,313 --> 00:34:01,012
Do all of you plan on using it?

574
00:34:01,014 --> 00:34:04,082
Our hope is eventually
everyone in Alisandre will.

575
00:34:04,084 --> 00:34:05,517
AKAE: Why would they?

576
00:34:05,519 --> 00:34:09,120
Everyone believes
immortality is a gift.

577
00:34:09,122 --> 00:34:11,690
Do you?

578
00:34:13,460 --> 00:34:17,128
Everyone believes it's a gift,
as you say,

579
00:34:17,130 --> 00:34:19,664
because the Maintenance
they're taking every single day

580
00:34:19,666 --> 00:34:21,599
makes them believe
that that's true.

581
00:34:23,036 --> 00:34:25,603
Which is why
we're hoping to alter

582
00:34:25,605 --> 00:34:27,372
a single batch
of the Maintenance

583
00:34:27,374 --> 00:34:29,641
to create a short-term effect.

584
00:34:31,311 --> 00:34:33,778
A temporary experience,
if you will.

585
00:34:33,780 --> 00:34:36,715
A small window in time
in which members of this society

586
00:34:36,717 --> 00:34:39,551
might actually be able to
process what we're saying.

587
00:34:39,553 --> 00:34:43,455
Are there any long-term effects
or permanent damage?

588
00:34:43,457 --> 00:34:45,623
Certainly no damage.

589
00:34:45,625 --> 00:34:47,826
And as for long-term effects,

590
00:34:47,828 --> 00:34:49,627
that's the goal,

591
00:34:49,629 --> 00:34:51,296
isn't it?

592
00:34:51,298 --> 00:34:53,898
The problem with the plan
is that they...

593
00:34:58,672 --> 00:35:04,542
..we don't have access
to the Maintenance supply.

594
00:35:04,544 --> 00:35:07,579
It's stored
in a very secure facility.

595
00:35:07,581 --> 00:35:10,715
A facility
adjacent to Nescience.

596
00:35:12,386 --> 00:35:14,352
That's why I'm here.

597
00:35:14,354 --> 00:35:16,087
Because of where I work.

598
00:35:28,935 --> 00:35:31,269
What did it feel like to you

599
00:35:31,271 --> 00:35:33,171
when I died?

600
00:35:35,809 --> 00:35:38,910
Why do you continue to ask
that question?

601
00:35:41,515 --> 00:35:43,248
Do you expect
a different answer?

602
00:35:43,250 --> 00:35:45,583
Tell me again.

603
00:35:46,787 --> 00:35:49,988
(WISTFUL MUSIC)

604
00:35:53,927 --> 00:35:56,561
Losing your mother
was more than I could bear.

605
00:35:57,297 --> 00:35:59,664
And then to lose you...

606
00:36:04,671 --> 00:36:09,707
There were days when the pain
was so overwhelming

607
00:36:09,709 --> 00:36:14,612
that I didn't think
I could carry on.

608
00:36:16,783 --> 00:36:19,417
You were close -

609
00:36:19,419 --> 00:36:22,420
so close to being able
to save me.

610
00:36:22,422 --> 00:36:24,656
After I lost you, I...

611
00:36:25,392 --> 00:36:28,560
..I made Helias
promise me that...

612
00:36:29,629 --> 00:36:31,963
..that under no circumstances
would we leave the lab

613
00:36:31,965 --> 00:36:36,034
until we were certain
that we had it right.

614
00:36:36,770 --> 00:36:40,605
Until we knew for sure
that the Code,

615
00:36:40,607 --> 00:36:44,776
the genetic modifier
we had created,

616
00:36:44,778 --> 00:36:46,911
was the key to immortality.

617
00:36:50,250 --> 00:36:51,983
And that's what we did.

618
00:36:53,220 --> 00:36:55,186
But Helias left.

619
00:36:59,593 --> 00:37:02,393
He thought I took
too much of the credit,

620
00:37:02,395 --> 00:37:06,397
which was not my intention.

621
00:37:06,399 --> 00:37:11,569
But I was the driving force.

622
00:37:13,006 --> 00:37:16,741
That part of the story changes
every time you tell it.

623
00:37:19,346 --> 00:37:21,579
I found what the Pilot
is looking for.

624
00:37:21,581 --> 00:37:25,517
The virus,
only it's not a virus.

625
00:37:25,519 --> 00:37:27,585
It's a Code Diffuser.

626
00:37:27,587 --> 00:37:30,989
It changes it in some way.
Reduces it.

627
00:37:30,991 --> 00:37:32,824
Changes the Code?

628
00:37:32,826 --> 00:37:37,996
I wanted to believe that
somehow the Pilot was wrong,

629
00:37:37,998 --> 00:37:39,697
that there weren't people
like this.

630
00:37:39,699 --> 00:37:41,666
ARMAROS: The Pilot
is never wrong.

631
00:37:41,668 --> 00:37:43,968
Is there anything else?

632
00:37:45,272 --> 00:37:48,439
They want me to help them access
the Maintenance facility.

633
00:37:48,441 --> 00:37:50,542
What? Why?

634
00:37:50,544 --> 00:37:52,844
They want to alter
a batch of Maintenance.

635
00:37:52,846 --> 00:37:55,680
- For themselves?
- For everyone.

636
00:37:55,682 --> 00:37:58,249
They want to clear everyone
from what they believe to be

637
00:37:58,251 --> 00:38:03,388
some sort of mental fog
induced by Maintenance.

638
00:38:03,390 --> 00:38:04,956
For what purpose?

639
00:38:04,958 --> 00:38:07,859
They want to tell everyone
about the diffuser,

640
00:38:07,861 --> 00:38:12,931
to convince everyone
that we should be mortal.

641
00:38:12,933 --> 00:38:14,899
ARMAROS: Mortal.

642
00:38:16,102 --> 00:38:17,602
What did you tell them?

643
00:38:17,604 --> 00:38:19,804
I told them I couldn't do it.

644
00:38:19,806 --> 00:38:23,308
It's far too risky.
What if they succeed?

645
00:38:23,310 --> 00:38:26,778
These poor
delusional individuals.

646
00:38:26,780 --> 00:38:28,413
They're not on
their Maintenance.

647
00:38:28,415 --> 00:38:30,615
Their minds are unclear.

648
00:38:30,617 --> 00:38:34,085
Why would you ever want to
disrupt a perfect world?

649
00:38:36,856 --> 00:38:39,257
MASIM: What is it
that brought you back to us?

650
00:38:40,193 --> 00:38:44,996
I'm here because I can help you
access the Maintenance facility.

651
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:49,133
Are you sure
you want to do that?

652
00:38:49,135 --> 00:38:53,037
It's not a mission
without grave risk.

653
00:38:53,039 --> 00:38:54,539
I'm sure.

654
00:38:54,541 --> 00:38:56,674
(DYNAMIC MUSIC)

655
00:38:56,676 --> 00:38:59,544
I told you there's no
surveillance in this area.

656
00:38:59,546 --> 00:39:01,813
No-one uses these walkways
anymore.

657
00:39:05,218 --> 00:39:07,318
(DOOR RATTLES)

658
00:39:08,388 --> 00:39:10,154
(BEEPS AND WARBLES)

659
00:39:11,257 --> 00:39:12,457
(DOOR RATTLES)

660
00:39:12,459 --> 00:39:14,325
- LOGOS: Why is it locked?
- I don't know.

661
00:39:14,327 --> 00:39:16,861
- The scanner's not working.
- I knew she wouldn't help us.

662
00:39:16,863 --> 00:39:19,263
That's not it.
This is an antiquated device.

663
00:39:19,265 --> 00:39:21,933
Alright, let's go.

664
00:39:21,935 --> 00:39:23,668
Let's go.

665
00:39:31,111 --> 00:39:33,811
- Which way?
- Let's stick to the exit plan.

666
00:39:33,813 --> 00:39:36,314
You guys go that way
and we'll go through Nescience.

667
00:39:45,225 --> 00:39:47,325
Hello, Logos.

668
00:39:51,064 --> 00:39:52,764
Akae.

669
00:39:54,801 --> 00:39:56,434
You should be proud.

670
00:39:56,436 --> 00:39:59,404
The Pilot is delighted with you.

671
00:40:01,241 --> 00:40:03,241
What?

672
00:40:03,243 --> 00:40:05,810
You're... you're a guardian?

673
00:40:07,213 --> 00:40:08,680
I...

674
00:40:10,884 --> 00:40:12,383
Akae.

675
00:40:12,385 --> 00:40:14,118
You lied to me.

676
00:40:17,957 --> 00:40:21,259
I could not tell you I was
a watcher and you know that.

677
00:40:21,261 --> 00:40:23,361
(GRUNTS)

678
00:40:28,201 --> 00:40:30,702
(DEVICE ZINGS)

679
00:40:32,205 --> 00:40:36,407
Akae, you have done an admirable
service for our society.

680
00:40:38,712 --> 00:40:40,978
Thank you.

681
00:40:41,748 --> 00:40:43,848
Do you have a question?

682
00:40:43,850 --> 00:40:45,817
Something concerning you?

683
00:40:48,188 --> 00:40:49,854
I do.

684
00:40:50,690 --> 00:40:52,724
When can I see Logos?

685
00:40:53,993 --> 00:40:55,860
I'm afraid
that's not possible.

686
00:40:55,862 --> 00:40:58,896
I lied to him for my own gain

687
00:40:58,898 --> 00:41:00,665
and I'd like to apologise.

688
00:41:00,667 --> 00:41:03,868
Well, that's a lovely gesture,
Akae,

689
00:41:03,870 --> 00:41:07,105
but the Logos you knew is gone.

690
00:41:08,341 --> 00:41:10,174
In order to rehabilitate him,

691
00:41:10,176 --> 00:41:15,813
to free him from his unnatural
desire for mortality,

692
00:41:15,815 --> 00:41:18,916
we had to erase his mind,
his memories,

693
00:41:18,918 --> 00:41:21,285
everything that made him
who he was.

694
00:41:22,188 --> 00:41:24,622
It's for the better,
I assure you.

695
00:41:25,358 --> 00:41:28,793
You should feel a great sense of
pride for the work you've done.

696
00:41:32,799 --> 00:41:34,999
Is there anything else
you haven't told us?

697
00:41:35,001 --> 00:41:36,300
No.

698
00:41:37,437 --> 00:41:38,870
Thank you.

699
00:41:38,872 --> 00:41:41,205
There is one thing.

700
00:41:43,009 --> 00:41:45,376
I'd like to remain at Nescience.

701
00:41:45,378 --> 00:41:48,679
A guardian office awaits you
at the capital.

702
00:41:48,681 --> 00:41:50,681
It's where I feel comfortable.

703
00:41:50,683 --> 00:41:52,950
Then that's where you'll stay.

704
00:42:07,734 --> 00:42:09,500
(SIGHS)

705
00:42:17,544 --> 00:42:20,945
(WISTFUL MUSIC)

706
00:42:44,637 --> 00:42:46,370
He's in Daden.

